value.value: The directed movement of the centrosome to a specific location.
Any process in which a centrosome is maintained in a specific location within a cell and prevented from moving elsewhere.

label.value: oocyte nucleus localization involved in oocyte dorsal/ventral axis specification

value.value: The directed movement of the nucleus to a specific location within a cell during the establishment and maintenance of the dorsal/ventral axis of the oocyte.
Any process in which nuclear pores are transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.

Any process in which membrane rafts are transported to, or maintained in, a specific location. Membrane rafts are small (10-200 nm), heterogeneous, highly dynamic, sterol- and sphingolipid-enriched membrane domains that compartmentalize cellular processes.

Any process in which actin cortical patches are transported to, or maintained in, a specific location. An actin cortical patch is a discrete actin-containing structure found just beneath the plasma membrane in fungal cells.
The directed movement of a plastid to a specific location in the cell.
Any process in which a substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within a membrane.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of terminal, non-reducing 2,1- and 2,6-linked beta-D-fructofuranose residues in fructans.
Catalysis of the endohydrolysis of 2,1-beta-D-fructosidic linkages in inulin.

label.value: disruption of plasma membrane integrity in another organism

value.value: The disruption of the cell membrane of another organism, leading to damage or temporary subversion of the membrane.
Any process in which a cell is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of pullulan to isopanose (6-alpha-maltosylglucose).
The chemical reactions and pathways involving pullulan, a neutral linear polysaccharide composed of repeating units of maltotriose joined by alpha-(1,6)-linkages.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of pullulan, a neutral linear polysaccharide composed of repeating units of maltotriose joined by alpha-(1,6)-linkages.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of pullulan, a neutral linear polysaccharide composed of repeating units of maltotriose joined by alpha-(1,6)-linkages.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving 6-alpha-maltosylglucose, also known as isopanose.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of 6-alpha-maltosylglucose, also known as isopanose.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of 6-alpha-maltosylglucose, also known as isopanose.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of galactomannan, a polysaccharide composed of D-galactosyl and D-mannosyl. The mannosyl units form the backbone structure (a linear main chain) with the D-galactosyl as single side units.
The directed movement of the Golgi to a specific location.
Any process in which the Golgi is maintained in a specific location within a cell and prevented from moving elsewhere.
Any process in which the endoplasmic reticulum is maintained in a specific location within a cell and prevented from moving elsewhere.
The directed movement of the endoplasmic reticulum to a specific location.
Any process in which the spindle is maintained in a specific location within a cell and prevented from moving elsewhere.
Any process in which a plastid is maintained in a specific location within a cell and prevented from moving elsewhere.
The binding of a protein or protein complex to the end of an actin filament, thus preventing the addition, exchange or removal of further actin subunits.
The binding of a protein or protein complex to the pointed (or minus) end of an actin filament, thus preventing the addition, exchange or removal of further actin subunits.
The removal of capping protein from the end of actin filaments to free the ends for addition, exchange or removal of further actin subunits.
The removal of capping protein from the pointed (or minus) end of actin filaments to free the ends for addition, exchange or removal of further actin subunits.
The breakage of covalent bonds to detach lipid groups from a protein.
Catalysis of the reaction: H2O + L-saccharopine + O2 = (S)-2-amino-6-oxohexanoate + H2O2 + L-glutamate.
Catalysis of the reaction: fructosyl-amino acid + O2 = corresponding amino acid + glucosone + H2O2.

label.value: biological process involved in interaction with host

value.value: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association. The term host is used for the larger (macro) of the two members of a symbiosis; the various forms of symbiosis include parasitism, commensalism and mutualism.

label.value: biological process involved in interaction with symbiont

value.value: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association. The term symbiont is used for the smaller (macro) of the two members of a symbiosis; the various forms of symbiosis include parasitism, commensalism and mutualism.

label.value: biological process involved in intraspecies interaction between organisms

value.value: Any process in which an organism has an effect on an organism of the same species.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from another living organism.

label.value: regulation of killing of cells of another organism

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the killing by an organism of cells in another organism.

label.value: negative regulation of killing of cells of another organism

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the killing by an organism of cells in another organism.

label.value: positive regulation of killing of cells of another organism

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the killing by an organism of cells in another organism.
The killing by an organism of a cell in another organism by means of the rupture of cell membranes and the loss of cytoplasm.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus. The process begins with detection of the stimulus by a cell and ends with a change in state or activity or the cell.

label.value: DNA (cytosine-5-)-methyltransferase activity, acting on CpG substrates

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methionine + CpG (in DNA) = S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + 5-MeCpG (in DNA).

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methionine + DNA containing CpNpG = S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + DNA containing 5-MeCpNpG.
Binding to protein phosphatase 2A.
Catalysis of the reaction: C-terminal protein amino acid methyl ester + H2O = protein amino acid + methanol.
Catalysis of the reaction: protein amino acid methyl ester + H2O = protein amino acid + methanol.
Enables the transfer of NAD from one side of a membrane to the other.
